The South Village Historic District is bounded from North to South by West 4th to West Houston, and from East to West by Laguardia Place to 6th Ave. The earliest known purpose-built tenement erected in this historic district stands at 169 Thompson Street. "New York’s long history with the ready-to-wear apparel industry had an ugly beginning — the manufacture of clothing for Southern slaves. The disaster at the Triangle Factory Fire in 1911 brought attention to the terrible conditions found in New York’s new loft-style factories. Office and residential, "The Garment District in Midtown Manhattan has been the center for all things American fashion for almost one hundred years. In addition to large dry goods stores like Arnold Constable at East 19th Street and Lord & Taylor at East 20th Street, Broadway contained retail establishments specializing in the sale of household furnishings like W. & J. Sioane, the furniture and decorating establishment of David S. Hess, and A. A. Vantine, "The Oriental Store" specializing in goods from the Middle and Far East (all between East 18th and East 19th Streets), as well as smaller specialty shops, many of which located in altered row-houses or in the ground-story shopfronts of larger office and loft buildings. Commercial Office Building, "43 West 24th Street is adjacent to the Ladies Mile Historic District.The Ladies Mile Historic District takes its name from the stretch of Broadway, which in the last third of the 19th century was lined by fashionable shops and stores. Broadway, beginning in the late 1850s, became the city's most exclusive shopping street catering to the ""carriage trade,"" a role which intensified in the years following the Civil War and well into the 1880s. In the 1890’s -1915, this neighborhood was home to the rise of the ready- to-wear industry, with New York as the center of an industry serving a national market.

space_distr: In the decades following the opening of Madison Square in 1847, numerous houses were built along the north and east sides of the park, as well as in the surrounding blocks. Heirs to the Varian and Samler estates began to partition their properties in the 1830s, selling lots to both private individuals and speculative builders. The typical pattern was to divide the blocks into lots twenty or twenty-five feet wide and one hundred feet deep. The majority of residences were brick or brownstone-fronted buildings in the prevailing Italianate style.
